[codex] In our studies, we make no assumptions about the normative or ΓÇ£appropriateΓÇ¥ level for any attribute in the absence of explicit goals or prescriptions. We expect that a reputational or image concern is activated only after participants receive descriptive feedback, and only for race and gender. This fits the theoretical framing already in the paper: descriptive feedback shifts behavior on a given dimension only when that dimension carries an implicit injunctive norm that the feedback calls into question. We argue this holds for race and gender but not for the comparison attributes we test (as previously discussed in the Introduction, p. X, and General Discussion, p. X). However, we have now added several sentences to the Introduction (p. X) and as a footnote in our Discussion of Study 4 (p. X), making explicit both that descriptive feedback shifts subsequent selections only on dimensions carrying an implicit injunctive norm and that we do not assume participantsΓÇÖ initial selections reflect any particular benchmark or ΓÇ£appropriateΓÇ¥ level for the comparison attributes.
[codex] Additional analysis: Although we donΓÇÖt have data to perfectly speak to this, we conducted an additional analysis to try to address this concern. We can hold the starting point constant by restricting to participants whose initial selections contained zero of the focal attribute. We cannot directly measure what each participant considers an ΓÇ£appropriateΓÇ¥ level for a given attribute, but zero is a reasonable floor and is unlikely to reflect a deliberate level for most participants. In this analysis, we test the hypothesis that feedback motivates selection whenever the initial selections do not reflect appropriate levels. If that were the case, we should see feedback move participants for both race and gender and the comparison attributes in this subset. To test this hypothesis, we pooled participants across Studies 2, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B with participant-clustered standard errors, restricted to participant observations in which the initial selection contained zero of the focal attribute. We find that among participants who selected zero women or racial minorities initially, race and gender feedback increases the probability of selecting a woman or racial minority as their final selection by +21.28 percentage points (p < .001, N = 1,222 across all five studies). Among participants who selected zero individuals any of the other attributes, feedback about these other attributes increases the probability of selecting an additional individual with that attribute by only +6.83 percentage points, and is not statistically significant (p = .21, N = 429). A Wald test of the difference between the two pooled coefficients yields +14.46 percentage points (p = .016, 95% CI [+2.70, +26.21]). See Table R1 for full results.  We have also added a footnote to the Discussion of Study 4 (p. X) that summarizes this evidence
[codex] However, we acknowledge that the comparison side of this analysis is meaningfully underpowered, so we can only provide suggestive evidence of our claims. Moreover, we further recognize that zero is a useful but imperfect floor, since for some participants it may reflect a deliberate preference. For these reasons, we treat this analysis as imperfect but directional evidence against the alternative that participants are selecting comparison attributes at appropriate levels to begin with.
