[codex] Thanks for the opportunity to review this paper, which has improved substantially since the last round. I appreciate the authorsΓÇÖ attentiveness to most of the comments raised previously. After reading this version, I have two comments.
[codex] RESPONSE: Thank you for your kind words about how much you feel our manuscript has improved. We are grateful for your feedback, which we feel has helped us improve the paper immensely.
[codex] First, the paper, as written, feels a bit dated in several spots (e.g., early intro, then pp.4-5, and Discussion) given all that has transpired with respect to pull back on DEI commitments and practices in the US. ItΓÇÖs not clear how many companies are still providing diversity scorecards or numerical feedback about demographic representation, but itΓÇÖs certainly a smaller number than when this research project began, and perhaps, more importantly, the broader tides have shifted. The one sentence on p.5 ΓÇô ΓÇ£and despiteΓÇªΓÇ¥ - is not sufficient and is perhaps misleading. The authors should find a way to acknowledge this through the narrative, and more accurately depict the current state so that the article does not feel timestamped and detached as if it was written in a pre-2024 period. While doing this, they should find a way to reinforce the reasons why their question and intervention remain important.
[codex] RESPONSE: Thank you for this comment. We have updated the Introduction (pp. X) and the Discussion to situate the paper more explicitly in the current socio-political landscape with respect to DEI efforts.
[codex] The revised manuscript now more thoroughly discusses the fluctuating corporate posture toward DEI over the past five years: a period in which many U.S. organizations first rapidly adopted pro-DEI rhetoric and commitments, and then many of those same organizations have since scaled back on those commitments under new political, legal, and reputational pressures. At the same time, we also acknowledge three countervailing patterns that have occurred in parallel. First, internationally, regulatory demand for transparency around demographic representation is expanding. For example, AustraliaΓÇÖs Workplace Gender Equality Amendment (Closing the Gender Pay Gap) Act 2023 mandates public reporting of firm-level gender representation and pay-gap data (Ressia, 2024); the EU Pay Transparency Directive 2023/970 requires member-state transposition by June 2026 (Mignano, 2024); and the EU Women on Boards Directive 2022/2381 establishes a 40% representation objective for the underrepresented gender on listed-company boards. Second, within the U.S., public and stakeholder sentiment has shifted more slowly than corporate and legal rhetoric. For instance a 2025 Bentley/Gallup survey reports that 69% of U.S. adults believe businesses should promote DEI (Bentley/Gallup, 2025), and anti-DEI shareholder proposals have failed at numerous prominent organizations, including Costco, Apple, LeviΓÇÖs, John Deere, Goldman Sachs, and others (CBS, 2025; Marketplace, 2025). Third, within corporations, many firms appear to have rebranded or reframed diversity-related work rather than dismantling it entirely. For example, Constellation Brands now uses ΓÇ£Inclusive Culture Team,ΓÇ¥ KohlΓÇÖs has shifted to ΓÇ£Chief Inclusion and Belonging Officer,ΓÇ¥ and Nationwide and UPS have migrated toward ΓÇ£belonging,ΓÇ¥ ΓÇ£respect,ΓÇ¥ ΓÇ£fairness,ΓÇ¥ or ΓÇ£inclusive experiencesΓÇ¥ framings (CNBC, 2025; HRGrapevine, 2025; Marketplace, 2026). Consistent with this pattern, Paradigm reports a 22% decrease in Fortune 100 references to ΓÇ£DEI/diversityΓÇ¥ between 2023 and 2024 alongside a 59% increase in references to ΓÇ£belongingΓÇ¥ (Paradigm, 2025).Together, Incorporating these developments also helped us sharpen why the paperΓÇÖs central question remains important in the current climate. The paperΓÇÖs contribution is not simply that descriptive feedback may serve as a useful managerial tool, but that descriptive feedback about past selection patterns can change subsequent decisions when those patterns raise concerns about appearing prejudiced or failing to live up to your own egalitarian standards. The recent pullback from explicit DEI rhetoric in U.S. organizations is therefore relevant to the scope of our theory. To the extent that corporate messaging and formal diversity commitments are one source of peopleΓÇÖs motivation to respond without prejudice, their retreat may weaken that pathway. At the same time, these organizational cues are not the only source of such concerns. Anti-discrimination law, international transparency requirements, employee and stakeholder expectations, and individualsΓÇÖ own egalitarian commitments can continue to make race and gender consequential dimensions of evaluation, even when organizations no longer foreground DEI language. Thus, the current landscape does not simply make the paper less timely; it helps clarify when descriptive feedback should be more or less likely to matter. We now explain that descriptive feedback should be most influential when past selection patterns raise active concerns about prejudice, and less influential in contexts where those concerns are absent, muted, or explicitly rejected. Practically, this also reinforces the relevance of studying descriptive feedback as a light-touch approach: in settings where organizations are reluctant to issue explicit diversity goals, it remains important to understand whether making past selection patterns visible can still shape who is subsequently selected, hired, promoted, platformed, or featured.
