[codex] Somewhat related, I still think more can be done to make the case for the theoretical contribution. Here is one way I think the authors can do this. I think they can start with language that more tentatively bounds the scope and generalizability of the authorsΓÇÖ claims. It currently reads as if this intervention would work similarly in any organizational context. But if the entire process hinges on the motivation to not appear prejudiced, it stands to reason that this motivation will not be the same across culturally heterogeneous organizations, some of which tightly identify with egalitarian ideals and inclusion, whereas others do not, and have recently retreated and even disavowed these ΓÇ£wokeΓÇ¥ metrics in place of a sole focus on merit. The fact that individualsΓÇÖ political ideology (perhaps an indirect proxy for motivation to respond without prejudice) did not work out in Study 4, leaves this somewhat unaddressed empirically. There is a tension here because the author also underscore this motivation to respond without prejudice as central to their theoretical contribution (one of two main contributions). To really nail this mechanism more definitively and show scope conditions (both of which can help solidify the contribution), I could imagine a study in which the authors more directly manipulated aspects of the situation to increase or decrease individualsΓÇÖ motivation to respond without prejudice and then measured the effects on subsequent decision making. This would help them more compellingly account for when these effects do vs do not emerge and why. There are already a bunch of studies in this package, however, so whether the authors should engage this issue empirically or narratively is a question for the editorial team.
[codex] RESPONSE: Thank you for this thoughtful comment. As you note, we did test whether political ideology moderated our effect in Study 4 and overall observed no significant interaction. While we are cautious about over-interpreting null results, the pattern is suggestive that the effect operates across partisan lines, leaving room for the external and internal motivations described above to be at work. Consistent with this interpretation, another recent study by Kirgios et al. (2022) found in a field experiment that when seeking help from city counselors, women and racial minorities benefited from explicitly naming their demographic identity in an ask just as much when contacting Republicans and Democrats, and the underlying mechanism identified was a motivation to control prejudice - the same mechanism we identify as mediating our findings. Overall, the existing empirical evidence suggests political ideology does not seem to moderate motivation to control prejudice.
[codex] Regarding your request for additional data, we share your view that there are already many studies in this package and have sought to engage with the important issues you raise narratively rather than empirically (this also aligns with the DEΓÇÖs guidance to prioritize streamlining the manuscript and not listing additional data to address this point as a requirement).  Specifically, we have sought to sharpen our discussion of our theoretical contribution in the revised General Discussion (pp. X), building on the scope-condition discussion already present in the Future Directions and Limitations section.
[codex] In particular, we now explicitly distinguish between two pathways through which descriptive feedback can change selection decisions. One pathwayΓÇôthe external motivation to control prejudiceΓÇôshould be driven both by a firmΓÇÖs norms but also by the fact that selection decisions are often observable to colleagues, job candidates, supervisors, and other stakeholders, and the implicit norm against prejudicial behavior is largely sustained by anti-discrimination laws, employee and customer scrutiny, and broader reputational concerns. The second pathwayΓÇôinternal motivation to control prejudiceΓÇôby contrast, refers to selectorsΓÇÖ personally held egalitarian beliefs and self-image as non-prejudiced decision-makers. This second pathway should not vary with organizational climate, and it is the pathway most directly supported by Study 4 (a study in which feedback was delivered privately and internal motivation to respond without prejudice mediated subsequent selections).
[codex] As we note in the General Discussion, we view motivation to respond without prejudice as one key mechanism we isolate, but not the only one descriptive feedback can plausibly activate. Fairness norms and broader concerns about appropriate representation may also drive the effects of feedback about past selections on future selection decisions (see also Study 5ΓÇÖs mechanism analysis, which found that fairness concerns drive people to select men when women are overrepresented in order to reduce gender imbalance). We now describe further research probing these additional plausible mechanisms as a promising direction for future research. 
