[codex] > In particular, we now explicitly distinguish between two pathways through which descriptive feedback can change selection decisions. One pathwayΓÇôthe external motivation to control prejudiceΓÇôshould be driven both by a firm's norms but also by the fact that selection decisions are often observable to colleagues, job candidates, supervisors, and other stakeholders, and the implicit norm against prejudicial behavior is largely sustained by anti-discrimination laws, employee and customer scrutiny, and broader reputational concerns. The second pathwayΓÇôinternal motivation to control prejudiceΓÇôby contrast, refers to selectors' personally held egalitarian beliefs and self-image as non-prejudiced decision-makers. This second pathway should not vary with organizational climate, and it is the pathway most directly supported by Study 4 (a study in which feedback was delivered privately and internal motivation to respond without prejudice mediated subsequent selections).
[codex] 
[codex] **What the manuscript already says.** The two-pathway distinction is threaded throughout: paragraph 14 ("driven by both external reputational concerns and internal desires to maintain a positive self-view"); paragraph 17 (same); paragraph 167 ("both internal and external motivation to respond without prejudice mediates the relationship"); paragraph 170 ("internal and external motivation to respond without prejudice"); paragraph 176 ("the primary driver of the effect of feedback was to trigger internal motivation to respond without prejudice, which may be because the delivery of feedback was private. However, if feedback were instead delivered publicly... external motivation to respond without prejudice could become a greater propellant"). The enhancement sharpens the distinction in paragraph 170 with three additional sentences and adds the Levi & Fried (2024) citation for the "DEI rhetoric as downstream signal" claim, plus a bridge sentence connecting Study 4B's political-ideology null to both pathways.
[codex] 
[codex] ### CURRENT (paragraph 170)
[codex] > Our work makes two primary theoretical contributions. First, we offer new insights about how and when descriptive feedback motivates behavior change. According to Feedback Intervention Theory, feedback is most effective when paired with explicit goals, standards, or explicit injunctive norms that signal a clear gap between current performance and a desired state (Kluger & DeNisi, 1996; Schultz et al., 2007). Purely descriptive feedback is often viewed as insufficient to drive change because it lacks a directive. We show that descriptive feedback can consistently motivate behavior change in the absence of explicit prescriptions. When such feedback targets DEI-relevant attributes of past selections and suggests women or minorities have been overlooked, the feedback itself elicits reputational or self-image concerns ΓÇô specifically, internal and external motivation to respond without prejudice. In the context of diversity, an explicit goal, target, social norm or injunctive norm does not need to be coupled with feedback to induce a response because an implicit injunctive norm to avoid prejudice has already been internalized by the decision-maker. This suggests that the utility of providing descriptive feedback absent an explicit goal, target or norm lies in its ability to focus attention on past behavior in arenas where individuals already harbor self-image or reputational concerns.
