[codex] > Our work makes two primary theoretical contributions. First, we offer new insights about how and when descriptive feedback motivates behavior change. According to Feedback Intervention Theory, feedback is most effective when paired with explicit goals, standards, or explicit injunctive norms that signal a clear gap between current performance and a desired state (Kluger & DeNisi, 1996[; Locke & Latham, 2019]; Schultz et al., 2007[; Schultz et al., 2018]). Purely descriptive feedback is often viewed as insufficient to drive change because it lacks a directive. We show that descriptive feedback can consistently motivate behavior change in the absence of explicit prescriptions. When such feedback targets DEI-relevant attributes of past selections and suggests women or minorities have been overlooked, the feedback itself elicits reputational or self-image concerns ΓÇô specifically, internal and external motivation to respond without prejudice. [These two pathways operate through distinct channels. External motivation to control prejudice should be strongest when selection decisions are observable to colleagues, candidates, supervisors, customers, employees, or stakeholders, and when evaluators face legal accountability or reputational consequences for choices that appear exclusionary; in this view, firms' public DEI rhetoric is one downstream signal of these broader legal, employee, customer, and reputational pressures rather than the source of the implicit injunctive norm itself (Levi & Fried, 2024). Internal motivation to control prejudice, by contrast, reflects selectors' personally held egalitarian beliefs and their desire to view themselves as non-prejudiced decision makers, and it is the pathway most directly supported by Study 4's private-feedback design. Study 4B's null moderation by political ideology is consistent with this account, suggesting that both pathways can operate across the partisan spectrum.] In the context of diversity, an explicit goal, target, social norm or injunctive norm does not need to be coupled with feedback to induce a response because an implicit injunctive norm to avoid prejudice has already been internalized by the decision-maker. This suggests that the utility of providing descriptive feedback absent an explicit goal, target or norm lies in its ability to focus attention on past behavior in arenas where individuals already harbor self-image or reputational concerns.
