[codex] Overview of Studies
[codex] We present seven pre-registered experiments (total N = 6,502), including one framed field experiment (Harrison & List, 2004), to examine how descriptive feedback about a portfolio of past choices affects subsequent selection decisions. In most of our studies, we employ a candidate selection paradigm illustrated in Figure 1. Participants begin by choosing a portfolio of six to seven candidates (e.g., panelists, authors) from a larger candidate pool including twenty-four to twenty-six options (in Study 1, participants are simply told to imagine they have made prior selections and informed about the composition of those prior selections). After making their initial selections (or being told about them in Study 1), participants are randomly assigned to receive two to three pieces of descriptive feedback summarizing the characteristics of their initial selectees. Participants assigned to a treatment condition receive feedback summarizing either the gender (Studies 1, 3B, 4B and 5) or racial (Studies 3A and 4A) composition of their initially selected candidates (e.g., the percentage who were female; the percentage who were racial minorities) alongside one or two pieces of additional descriptive feedback about their initially selected candidates to both (1) obfuscate the purpose of the research and (2) measure the impact of such feedback focused on non-DEI-related characteristics of past selectees (e.g., the percentage of prior selectees who were CEOs; the percentage who were genre-spanning writers). Participants assigned to the control condition also receive descriptive feedback about their initially selected candidates (e.g., the percentage who were technologists; the percentage who were born in the 1800s), but this feedback never references the race or gender composition of prior selectees. Finally, participants are given the opportunity to select one or more additional candidates to add to the group (e.g., of panelists or authors) that they just created. Our outcomes of interest are the attributes of these subsequent selecteesΓÇöand in particular, their gender (in Studies 1, 3B, 4B and 5) or race (in Studies 3A and 4A). Data for Studies 1ΓÇô5 as well as analysis code for all studies can be found on OSF: https://osf.io/zxyw2/.
[codex] ------------------------------------
[codex] Insert Figure 1 and 2 about here
[codex] ------------------------------------
[codex] We established across all seven experiments in this paper that in settings where women (or racial minorities) are underrepresented, providing descriptive feedback about the gender (or race) of past selectees alongside other feedback about past selecteesΓÇÖ characteristics increases evaluatorsΓÇÖ subsequent likelihood of selecting women (or racial minorities). In Study 2, we established the external validity of our findings through a framed field experiment (on a university campus). To further establish that our findings are not merely driven by a demand effect, we also showed that the effect of providing descriptive feedback about the gender or race of past selectees is reliably and significantly larger than that of providing descriptive feedback about other attributes of past selectees (e.g., the fraction in a given profession, the fraction in a given birth cohort) on participantsΓÇÖ likelihood of selecting candidates with those other attributes (e.g., a candidate in a given profession or a given birth cohort), even when those other attributes are rated as similarly important as candidatesΓÇÖ demographics (Studies 1, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B). In Studies 4A and 4B, we showed that motivation to respond without prejudice mediated the effect of providing descriptive feedback about the gender (or race) of past selectees on the likelihood of subsequently selecting a woman (or racial minority) candidate. And finally, in Study 5, we showed that providing feedback about the percentage of past selectees who were women only subsequently increased the selection of women when women are underrepresented in the initial candidate pool; when women are overrepresented, the effect is significantly smaller in magnitude and reverses in direction (decreasing the selection of women), and is mediated by fairness concerns rather than concerns about prejudice.
[codex] 
[codex] Study 1
[codex] 
[codex] In Study 1, participants imagined assuming the role of National Public Radio (NPR) producers selecting experts to interview for stories about the future of work in America. We tested the effect of providing participants with descriptive feedback about the gender composition of their previously selected expert sources on their subsequent hypothetical selections of experts for future NPR stories. This study was designed to imitate the real feedback system currently used at NPR to provide producers with summary statistics about their past sources (Fu, 2021).
[codex] Methods
[codex] Participants. As pre-registered (https://osf.io/vazsm/), we recruited 1,000 participants through Prolific to complete a 3-minute survey for $0.75 (55.4% women; 43.7% men; 0.9% non-binary; Mage = 43.80; 72.3% White, 13.2% Black, 6.5% Hispanic, 7.2% Asian).
[codex] Procedure. Participants were told to imagine they worked as producers at NPR and were responsible for identifying and booking expert sources to interview for various news segments and stories. Participants were informed that for the past three months, they had been working on a series of stories about the future of work in America and had selected and interviewed a portfolio of ten experts for these stories.
[codex] Participants were then randomly assigned to one of two conditions: (1) the no gender feedback condition or (2) the gender feedback condition. In the no gender feedback condition, participants received descriptive feedback summarizing the percentage of experts they had selected over the past three months who (1) were under 50 years old, (2) were based on the West Coast (of the United States), and (3) worked at a university. Notably, NPR has actually tracked each of these attributes of expert sources, which were deemed a priority, and displayed them to producers. In the gender feedback condition, participants always received feedback about the percentage of past selectees who were women, presented alongside two of the three statistics presented in the no gender feedback condition drawn at random. 
[codex] After receiving descriptive feedback about the composition of their past expert selections, participants were asked to select three experts from a list of 25 candidates for an upcoming NPR segment on how artificial intelligence is reshaping employment and were provided with each candidate's name, area of expertise, and institutional affiliation. See Materials Section: Study 1 in the Appendix for complete study materials.
[codex] ------------------------------------------------------------------
[codex] Insert Table 2 about here 
[codex] ------------------------------------------------------------------ 
[codex] Results
[codex] Following our pre-registration, we ran an ordinary least squares regression (OLS) predicting the proportion of women selected, with assignment to the gender feedback condition as our primary predictor and an indicator for assignment to stimulus Set 1.
[codex] As shown in Figure 3A and Model 1 of Table 2, participants selected a significantly higher proportion of women experts in the gender feedback condition (46.2% women experts selected) than in the no gender feedback condition (33.7% women experts selected; B = 0.125, 95% CI = [0.093, 0.157], t(997) = 7.58, p < .001). The effect was robust to controlling for participant demographics (Appendix Table S1).	To formally test whether offering feedback about the percentage of past experts who were women had a larger effect on the subsequent selection of women experts than offering feedback about other attributes had on the subsequent selection of experts with those attributes, we constructed three systems of simultaneous equations (Zellner, 1962). For each system, we included a pair of equations: one modeling the effect of random assignment to receive gender feedback and one modeling the effect of random assignment to receive feedback on another expert attribute (i.e., past selectees who were under 50 years old, based on the West Coast, or worked at a university, see Table 2, Models 5-8). We then used Wald tests to compare the treatment effects estimated in the paired equations, which confirmed that the effect of assignment to the gender feedback condition on the proportion of women experts selected was significantly larger than the effects of assignment to receive descriptive feedback about the percentage of past experts who were (1) under 50 years old (F(1, 3988) = 6.63, p = .010), (2) based on the West Coast (F(1, 3988) = 8.35, p = .004), or (3) worked at a university (F(1, 3988) = 12.84, p < .001) on subsequent selections of experts with those respective attributes. This pattern of findings held across stimuli sets (see footnote 2). 
[codex] Discussion
[codex] Study 1 mirrored a real organizational practice currently deployed by NPR and provides initial evidence that descriptive feedback about the gender composition of past selections can increase the subsequent selection of women, more so than feedback about other attributes. In our next study, we examine whether our effects hold when people make real, consequential decisions in the field rather than hypothetical choices in an online survey.
