[codex]   33: We established across all seven experiments in this paper that in settings where women (or racial minorities) are underrepresented, providing descriptive feedback about the gender (or race) of past selectees alongside other feedback about past selecteesΓÇÖ characteristics increases evaluatorsΓÇÖ subsequent likelihood of selecting women (or racial minorities). In Study 2, we established the external validity of our findings through a framed field experiment (on a university campus). To further establish that our findings are not merely driven by a demand effect, we also showed that the effect of providing descriptive feedback about the gender or race of past selectees is reliably and significantly larger than that of providing descriptive feedback about other attributes of past selectees (e.g., the fraction in a given profession, the fraction in a given birth cohort) on participantsΓÇÖ likelihood of selecting candidates with those other attributes (e.g., a candidate in a given profession or a given birth cohort), even when those other attributes are rated as similarly important as candidatesΓÇÖ demographics (Studies 1, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B). In Studies 4A and 4B, we showed that motivation to respond without prejudice mediated the effect of providing descriptive feedback about the gender (or race) of past selectees on the likelihood of subsequently selecting a woman (or racial minority) candidate. And finally, in Study 5, we showed that providing feedback about the percentage of past selectees who were women only subsequently increased the selection of women when women are underrepresented in the initial candidate pool; when women are overrepresented, the effect is significantly smaller in magnitude and reverses in direction (decreasing the selection of women), and is mediated by fairness concerns rather than concerns about prejudice.
[codex]   34: 
[codex]   35: Study 1
[codex]   36: 
[codex]   37: In Study 1, participants imagined assuming the role of National Public Radio (NPR) producers selecting experts to interview for stories about the future of work in America. We tested the effect of providing participants with descriptive feedback about the gender composition of their previously selected expert sources on their subsequent hypothetical selections of experts for future NPR stories. This study was designed to imitate the real feedback system currently used at NPR to provide producers with summary statistics about their past sources (Fu, 2021).
[codex]   38: Methods
[codex]   39: Participants. As pre-registered (https://osf.io/vazsm/), we recruited 1,000 participants through Prolific to complete a 3-minute survey for $0.75 (55.4% women; 43.7% men; 0.9% non-binary; Mage = 43.80; 72.3% White, 13.2% Black, 6.5% Hispanic, 7.2% Asian).
[codex]   40: Procedure. Participants were told to imagine they worked as producers at NPR and were responsible for identifying and booking expert sources to interview for various news segments and stories. Participants were informed that for the past three months, they had been working on a series of stories about the future of work in America and had selected and interviewed a portfolio of ten experts for these stories.
[codex]   41: Participants were then randomly assigned to one of two conditions: (1) the no gender feedback condition or (2) the gender feedback condition. In the no gender feedback condition, participants received descriptive feedback summarizing the percentage of experts they had selected over the past three months who (1) were under 50 years old, (2) were based on the West Coast (of the United States), and (3) worked at a university. Notably, NPR has actually tracked each of these attributes of expert sources, which were deemed a priority, and displayed them to producers. In the gender feedback condition, participants always received feedback about the percentage of past selectees who were women, presented alongside two of the three statistics presented in the no gender feedback condition drawn at random. 
[codex]   42: After receiving descriptive feedback about the composition of their past expert selections, participants were asked to select three experts from a list of 25 candidates for an upcoming NPR segment on how artificial intelligence is reshaping employment and were provided with each candidate's name, area of expertise, and institutional affiliation. See Materials Section: Study 1 in the Appendix for complete study materials.
