[codex]   33: RESPONSE: Thank you for the clear guidance and for offering to handle this revision yourself. A full overview of the most notable changes appears in the coverΓÇæletter summary above, and our detailed pointΓÇæbyΓÇæpoint replies to Reviewers 1 and 2 appear below.
[codex]   34: Reviewer 1 has asked for some updating of references and a bit of clarification in your writing.
[codex]   35: RESPONSE: We have addressed both points. The Introduction and General Discussion now draw on more contemporary work in the feedback, goalΓÇæsetting, and socialΓÇænorms literatures (e.g., Locke & Latham, 2019; Itzchakov & Latham, 2018; Chen, Latham, & Piccolo, 2020; Schultz, Nolan, & Cialdini, 2018; Devine & Ash, 2022; Andor, Gerster, & Peters, 2020; Henry, Ferraro, & Kontoleon, 2019; Mertens & Schultz, 2021), alongside the foundational citations we retain. We have also expanded the IntroductionΓÇÖs theoretical framing (pp. XΓÇæX) to clarify why descriptive feedback can shift selection decisions about women and underrepresented minorities even without a paired explicit goal: in this setting, we argue, feedback makes prior behavior salient against an implicit injunctive norm against prejudiced selection. We address Reviewer 1ΓÇÖs specific suggestions in detail below.
[codex]   36: Reviewer 3 has asked for a modification of some of the intro that wonΓÇÖt make this paper seem so ΓÇ£timestampedΓÇ¥. In addition, he/she has some questions about the theoretical positioning.  I think that the paper will be stronger if the authors address some of the ΓÇ£tensionΓÇ¥ the reviewer identifies with a study that provides more clarity, but I wonΓÇÖt make it a requirement. On the other hand, they should provide a more nuanced discussion of the issues the reviewer describes.
[codex]   37: RESPONSE: We have addressed these points in the Introduction (pp. X) and General Discussion (pp. X). To avoid making the paper read as if it were written in a preΓÇæ2024 period, we now acknowledge the recent U.S. retreat from explicit DEI rhetoric while also documenting countervailing patterns that keep the paperΓÇÖs central question relevant: expanded international transparency requirements, continued U.S. public and stakeholder support for corporate DEI, and firmΓÇælevel rebranding of diversity work toward ΓÇ£belonging,ΓÇ¥ ΓÇ£inclusive culture,ΓÇ¥ and related framings rather than wholesale dismantling.
[codex]   38: We have also made the theoretical scope conditions more explicit. In the revised manuscript, we acknowledge that pullbacks from explicit DEI commitments may reduce one source of pressure on decision-makers. At the same time, we explain that organizational commitments are not the only reason people may care about the demographic patterns in their selections. Anti-discrimination law, the visibility of selection decisions, employee and stakeholder expectations, broader reputational concerns, and individualsΓÇÖ own egalitarian commitments may all continue to make race and gender consequential in selection contexts. As a result, we now state more clearly that descriptive feedback should be most likely to matter when past selection patterns raise concerns about prejudice, and less likely to matter when those concerns are absent, muted, or explicitly rejected. Consistent with your note that an additional study is not required, and with your separate request to streamline the manuscript, we address this issue narratively rather than empirically. Our point-by-point reply to Reviewer 2 provides the supporting detail and citations, and the General Discussion now identifies organizational DEI climate as an important scope condition and direction for future research.
[codex]   39: I have two remaining requests, one about style and one about analysis.  Although the paper is generally well-written and the studies are well-designed, I found reading the paper a bit of a slog.  Some of that is that much of the analysis was nearly identical across studies, and the repetitive style of reporting made the paper feel bulky.  I understand that my tastes for writing and streamlining might be idiosyncratic, but I wonder if there can be streamlining (as in Figure 2) in which some of the repeated analysis (like comparison between the theoretically targeted feedback and the ΓÇ£controlΓÇ¥ feedback) shows up in a Table with the relevant statistics.  I wonΓÇÖt make this a requirement, but IΓÇÖd like the authors to take this feedback (no pun intended) seriously and consider whether there is something that can be done.  I will also add that the paper right now is close to the page limit since you have moved the figures and tables out of the main text (ΓÇ£All invited revisions must adhere to the following page limit: 47 pages with 25 lines of text per page (double spacing) or 32 pages with 33 lines of text per page (1.5 spacing). An online appendix will not count toward the page limit.ΓÇ¥ https://pubsonline.informs.org/page/mnsc/submission-guidelines)
[codex]   40: RESPONSE: We thank you for this feedback and agree that the prior versionΓÇÖs repeated presentation of the same comparisons made the empirical sections longer than warranted. The revised manuscript is now [X] pages and reflects a substantial streamlining of the Methods and Results sections, particularly for later studies to avoid unnecessary repetition/redundancy. To that end, and following your guidance, we have relegated the reporting of the regression specifications behind the secondary feedback-about-race/gender-versus-other-attribute comparisons to a dedicated section of the Appendix, with explicit references from each Results section. 
[codex]   41: I think that Study 4b goes a long way in terms of convincing me that there is something special about gender/racial etc representational feedback relative to feedback on other attributes.  One though and one request.  Although I think that the package of studies is very compelling, I still found myself wishing that you had tested whether the alternative descriptive feedback that you shared was on par with gender in terms of importance.  My intuition, for example, in Study 1 is that ΓÇ£(1) were under 50 years old, (2) were based on the West Coast (of the United States), and (3) worked at a universityΓÇ¥ would be seen as less important than gender.  Two suggestions -- you could get a separate group and ΓÇ£post-testΓÇ¥ some of these items and if they are as important or nearly as important report that.  If on the other hand, they are a lot less important, I would ask you to consider running Study 1 again so that the paper starts with a strong study.
[codex]   42: RESPONSE: Thank you for this suggestion. We ran the post-test you proposed and incorporated the result into the Discussion of Study 1 (p. X). We recruited N = 300 Prolific participants and randomly assigned each to rate, on a 1 to 7 importance scale, one of the four expert-attribute statements used in Study 1ΓÇÖs feedback manipulation, with the NPR producer framing held constant. Two of the three comparison attributes were rated significantly more important than the gender attribute (ΓÇ£were womenΓÇ¥; M = 3.64, SD = 1.76, n = 76): ΓÇ£worked at a universityΓÇ¥ (M = 4.67, SD = 1.60; t(148.8) = ΓêÆ3.76, p < .001, d = ΓêÆ0.61) and ΓÇ£were under 50 years oldΓÇ¥ (M = 4.44, SD = 1.73; t(149.0) = ΓêÆ2.81, p = .006, d = ΓêÆ0.46). The third, ΓÇ£based on the West Coast of the United States,ΓÇ¥ showed no significant difference in importance (M = 3.37, SD = 1.75; t(149.0) = 0.95, p = .343, d = +0.16). Differences in perceived importance therefore cannot account for why only feedback about gender moved subsequent selections in Study 1, consistent with our claim that descriptive feedback motivates behavior on dimensions carrying an implicit injunctive norm.
[codex]   43: On the request, I liked Study 4b and think that it does a good job of showing that feedback about gender is different than feedback about other important dimensions.  In addition, your studies show that gender/race feedback lead subjects to adjust their portfolios about the base rate.  That said, IΓÇÖm still left wondering whether your findings are showing what you say or it is just that people use these other measures appropriately in their initial selections.  IΓÇÖd like you to at least discuss this possibility, and perhaps there is additional analysis that you can do to address this.
[codex]   44: RESPONSE: Thank you for raising this alternative. We now both discuss it more clearly and add a follow-up analysis that attempts to address this point. 
[codex]   45: In our studies, we make no assumptions about the normative or ΓÇ£appropriateΓÇ¥ level for any attribute in the absence of explicit goals or prescriptions. We expect that a reputational or image concern is activated only after participants receive descriptive feedback, and only for race and gender. This fits the theoretical framing already in the paper: descriptive feedback shifts behavior on a given dimension only when that dimension carries an implicit injunctive norm that the feedback calls into question. We argue this holds for race and gender but not for the comparison attributes we test (as previously discussed in the Introduction, p. X, and General Discussion, p. X). However, we have now added several sentences to the Introduction (p. X) and as a footnote in our Discussion of Study 4 (p. X), making explicit both that descriptive feedback shifts subsequent selections only on dimensions carrying an implicit injunctive norm and that we do not assume participantsΓÇÖ initial selections reflect any particular benchmark or ΓÇ£appropriateΓÇ¥ level for the comparison attributes.
[codex]   46: Additional analysis: Although we donΓÇÖt have data to perfectly speak to this, we conducted an additional analysis to try to address this concern. We can hold the starting point constant by restricting to participants whose initial selections contained zero of the focal attribute. We cannot directly measure what each participant considers an ΓÇ£appropriateΓÇ¥ level for a given attribute, but zero is a reasonable floor and is unlikely to reflect a deliberate level for most participants. In this analysis, we test the hypothesis that feedback motivates selection whenever the initial selections do not reflect appropriate levels. If that were the case, we should see feedback move participants for both race and gender and the comparison attributes in this subset. To test this hypothesis, we pooled participants across Studies 2, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B with participant-clustered standard errors, restricted to participant observations in which the initial selection contained zero of the focal attribute. We find that among participants who selected zero women or racial minorities initially, race and gender feedback increases the probability of selecting a woman or racial minority as their final selection by +21.28 percentage points (p < .001, N = 1,222 across all five studies). Among participants who selected zero individuals any of the other attributes, feedback about these other attributes increases the probability of selecting an additional individual with that attribute by only +6.83 percentage points, and is not statistically significant (p = .21, N = 429). A Wald test of the difference between the two pooled coefficients yields +14.46 percentage points (p = .016, 95% CI [+2.70, +26.21]). See Table R1 for full results.  We have also added a footnote to the Discussion of Study 4 (p. X) that summarizes this evidence
[codex]   47: However, we acknowledge that the comparison side of this analysis is meaningfully underpowered, so we can only provide suggestive evidence of our claims. Moreover, we further recognize that zero is a useful but imperfect floor, since for some participants it may reflect a deliberate preference. For these reasons, we treat this analysis as imperfect but directional evidence against the alternative that participants are selecting comparison attributes at appropriate levels to begin with.
