[codex]  112: We next tested for both mediators in a multiple mediation model (as preregistered), which addressed address potential multicollinearity between these correlated measures (rΓÇë=ΓÇë0.72, p < 0.001). Once accounting for the correlation between constructs, internal motivation to respond without prejudice (indirect effect = 0.08, 95% CI = [0.042, 0.11]), significantly mediated the effect  whereas external motivation to respond without prejudice (indirect effect = -0.014, 95% CI = [-0.03, 0.00]) did not.  
[codex]  113: Study 4B
[codex]  114: In this study, we replicate our key findings from Study 4A, but this time we provide feedback about the gender (rather than race) of the initial selectees. Prior to this study, we conducted a pretest (N = 550) rating 21 candidate author attributes on importance for selecting authors (see Appendix Section S4 for full details); allowing us to select three comparison attributes that did not differ significantly from gender on rated importance.
[codex]  115: Given that liberals and conservatives differ not only in their attitudes toward diversity but also in their understanding of what diversity means (Howard, Cervone, & Motyl, 2022), and that recent research suggests diversity initiatives may produce divergent reactions across the political spectrum (Hachem & Dover, 2024), we also examine whether participantsΓÇÖ political ideology moderates the effect of providing descriptive feedback about the gender of past selectees.
[codex]  116: Methods
[codex]  117: 	Participants. As pre-registered (https://osf.io/de3bu/), we recruited 1,000 participants through Prolific Academic to complete a 3-minute survey for $0.75 (48.0% men, 50.7% women, 1.1% non-binary; Mage = 43.0; 75.9% White, 10.8% Black, 4.8% Hispanic, 8.0% Asian).
[codex]  118: Procedure. As in Study 4A, a list of 25 (real) authors was presented to each participant to consider for inclusion in a reading list for their local library. Each author was displayed with a photograph, the authorΓÇÖs name (e.g., Kurt Vonnegut), most notable work (e.g., Slaughterhouse-Five), an estimate of their most notable workΓÇÖs all-time sales and time in print (e.g., 800K copies sold, in print 56 years), their number of works authored (e.g., 14 books, 3 essays), and their genre(s) (e.g., Science Fiction, Satire). Six of the authors on this list (24%) were women.
[codex]  119: Following a similar procedure to the one described in Study 4A, participants were randomly assigned to one of two conditions: participants in the no gender feedback condition received summary statistics about the percentage of authors they had selected who (1) wrote works spanning multiple genres, (2) had at least one book with 30 million or more copies sold, and/or (3) had works that remained in continuous print for over 50 years. In the gender feedback condition, participants always received feedback about the percentage of authors they had selected who were women, alongside two randomly drawn pieces of feedback from the list of items in the no gender feedback condition. After receiving feedback, participants selected a seventh and final author to recommend for their local libraryΓÇÖs winter fiction reading list from the original candidate set, where their prior selections were highlighted. 
[codex]  120: After making all decisions, participants were asked questions to assess their internal (CronbachΓÇÖs ╬▒ = 0.93) and external (CronbachΓÇÖs ╬▒ = 0.89) motivation to respond without prejudice, which were identical to the questions in Study 4A except for word changes made to focus on avoiding gender prejudice rather than racial prejudice. See Materials Section: Study 4B for full study materials. 
[codex]  121: Political ideology. To measure participantsΓÇÖ political orientation, we used the 7-point political ideology scale from the American National Election Studies (ANES, 2022). Participants responded to the prompt ΓÇ£When it comes to politics, do you usually think of yourself as...?ΓÇ¥ on a scale ranging from 1 (Extremely liberal) to 7 (Extremely conservative), with 4 representing Moderate; middle of the road. This measure was centered at 4 (moderate) for analyses examining moderation effects.
[codex]  122: Political party affiliation. To assess participantsΓÇÖ political party identification, we adapted the party identification item from the American National Election Studies (ANES, 2022). Participants were asked ΓÇ£Generally speaking, do you usually think of yourself as a Republican, a Democrat, or an Independent?ΓÇ¥ and selected one of three options: Democrat, Republican, or Independent. For regression analyses, party affiliation was dummy coded with Republican as the reference category.
[codex]  123: Results 
[codex]  124: Initial selections featured women authors 25.3% of the time, with balance across conditions (p = .679; see Appendix Table S9).
[codex]  125: Following our pre-registration, we ran an OLS regressions with robust standard errors predicting whether the seventh and final author a participant selected was a woman, with assignment to the gender feedback condition as the primary predictor First, we replicated the primary findings from our previous studies (see Table S9 for complete regression results): participants were significantly more likely to choose a woman author as their final selectee in the gender feedback condition (41.48% chose a woman author) than in the no gender feedback condition (29.54% chose a woman author; B = 0.119, 95% CI = [0.060, 0.178], t(998) = 3.97, p < .001; Table S9, Model 1).
[codex]  126: In addition, as theorized, we found that the effect of providing descriptive feedback about the gender of initial selectees is significantly larger than the effect of providing descriptive feedback about whether participantsΓÇÖ initial selectees wrote works spanning multiple genres (F(1, 1992) = 37.92, p < .001), wrote at least one book with 30 million or more copies sold (F(1, 1992) = 11.48, p < .001), or wrote any works that remained in continuous print for over 50 years (F(1, 1992) = 9.01, p = .003; see Table S9, Models 5-8).
[codex]  127: Mediation. Following our pre-registration, we tested each proposed mediator independently using a 10,000-sample bootstrapped mediation model and a Sobel test (Imai et al., 2010). The 95% bias-corrected CI for the indirect effect of internal motivation to respond without prejudice excluded zero (indirect effect = 0.064, 95% CI = [0.037, 0.094]), suggesting that internal motivation partially accounted for the effect of assignment to the gender feedback condition on the likelihood of selecting a woman as the final author; the average causal mediation effect approach suggested that 53.9% of the effect occurred through internal motivation. Next, the 95% bias-corrected CI for the indirect effect of external motivation excluded zero (indirect effect = 0.030, 95% CI = [0.014, 0.048]), suggesting that external motivation likewise accounted for the effect; the average causal mediation effect approach suggested that 24.8% of the effect occurred through external motivation. 
