[codex]  225: ### CURRENT (paragraph 14)
[codex]  226: > We theorize that diversity-related descriptive feedback about selection decisions (e.g., the racial or gender composition of those selected for past opportunities) can be effective at promoting diversification in subsequent selection decisions even in the absence of an explicit goal or norm when it suggests past choices have lacked diversity. We further posit that such feedback can be more effective at influencing future choices than descriptive feedback about other features of selection decisions. Why? Because diversity-related feedback can draw attention to the potential reputational and self-image ramifications of choices even in the absence of an explicit goal. Specifically, we propose that when such feedback highlights the underrepresentation of women or racial minorities in past selections, it will raise concerns that past behavior could be seen as discriminatory and therefore risk rebuke. This is a reaction referred to as "motivation to respond without prejudice" (Plant & Devine, 1998), and it is driven by people's desire to (1) avoid negative repercussions from others (i.e., to protect their reputation; Leary & Kowalski, 1990; Lerner & Tetlock, 1999) and (2) maintain a positive self-view or self-image (Plant & Devine, 1998, 2009; Crandall & Eshleman, 2003; Apfelbaum et al., 2008).
