[codex] +> Our work focuses specifically on the effect of providing feedback about the race and gender composition of a portfolio of past selectees on future selectees. Race and gender are distinctive attributes in that they are often immediately visible, governed by strong normative prohibitions backed by legal frameworks, and carry clear consequences for both reputation and self-image (Apfelbaum et al., 2008; Crandall & Eshleman, 2003; Plant & Devine, 1998; Civil Rights Act of 1964). Consequently, our findings may not fully generalize to other attributes that signal a person can increase an organizationΓÇÖs diversity, such as their disability status, religious beliefs or sexuality, unless those attributes are made similarly visible. However, our theorizing suggests that descriptive feedback should influence behavior in any domain where the attributes it summarizes relate to similar implicit injunctive norms. Future research on this would be valuable. [Organizational DEI climate is a parallel scope condition. Descriptive feedback should matter most in organizations where past selection patterns raise active concerns about prejudice, because decisions are visible, egalitarian values are endorsed, or employees and stakeholders continue to treat race and gender representation as consequential. It should be weaker, and may not arise, in settings where both external accountability and internal egalitarian concerns are muted or openly rejected. Future work should directly test how descriptive feedback effects vary across organizations that differ in DEI climate.]
[codex] +
[codex] +**Notes.** I avoid saying the effect is weakest in ΓÇ£fully private settingsΓÇ¥ without qualification, because Study 4ΓÇÖs private-feedback design still produced an internal-motivation pathway. The limiting condition is better stated as the absence of both external and internal concerns.
